WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.100 --> 00:00:05.579
Concrete is the most widely used manufactured material on Earth.

2
00:00:05.579 --> 00:00:10.502
It forms our roads, our bridges, our dams, our foundations,

3
00:00:10.502 --> 00:00:16.092
and a growing share of the cities where most of humanity now lives.

4
00:00:16.092 --> 00:00:21.203
The binder that holds concrete together — ordinary Portland cement —

5
00:00:21.203 --> 00:00:26.013
is also one of the most carbon-intensive commodities we produce.

6
00:00:26.013 --> 00:00:32.880
Global cement manufacturing emits roughly 2.8 gigatons of CO2 per

7
00:00:32.880 --> 00:00:33.408
year.

8
00:00:33.408 --> 00:00:38.829
That's about 8 percent of all anthropogenic CO2 emissions.

9
00:00:38.829 --> 00:00:40.656
Unlike steel or ammonia,

10
00:00:40.656 --> 00:00:45.376
where renewable hydrogen and electric heating can in principle

11
00:00:45.376 --> 00:00:47.204
eliminate most emissions

12
00:00:47.204 --> 00:00:52.000
, roughly 60 percent of cement emissions are process emissions.

13
00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:57.907
The calcination of limestone releases CO2 regardless of the fuel

14
00:00:57.907 --> 00:00:58.553
source.

15
00:00:58.553 --> 00:01:03.452
Decarbonizing cement therefore requires new chemistries,

16
00:01:03.452 --> 00:01:05.289
not just clean kilns.

17
00:01:05.289 --> 00:01:08.882
This is a materials-discovery problem.

18
00:01:08.882 --> 00:01:13.809
The pathways to low-carbon cement — alternative binders,

19
00:01:13.809 --> 00:01:17.857
alternative clinkers, and CO2-cured concrete —

20
00:01:17.857 --> 00:01:22.433
all depend on phases that are amorphous, metastable,

21
00:01:22.433 --> 00:01:24.105
or multi-component.

22
00:01:24.105 --> 00:01:28.965
These are exactly the conditions where standard computational methods

23
00:01:28.965 --> 00:01:29.247
fail

24
00:01:29.247 --> 00:01:29.318
,

25
00:01:29.318 --> 00:01:33.473
and where universal machine-learning interatomic potentials

26
00:01:33.473 --> 00:01:37.066
systematically soften the potential energy surface.

27
00:01:37.066 --> 00:01:42.224
Lupine's correction-and-verification method was built for precisely

28
00:01:42.224 --> 00:01:44.303
this geometry of wrongness.

29
00:01:44.303 --> 00:01:49.040
It measures the error field over local coordination environments,

30
00:01:49.040 --> 00:01:51.737
adds analytic corrections at runtime,

31
00:01:51.737 --> 00:01:55.819
and proves which predictions are supported and which are

32
00:01:55.819 --> 00:01:57.276
synthesis-dependent.

33
00:01:57.276 --> 00:02:01.876
Portland cement is made by heating limestone, clay,

34
00:02:01.876 --> 00:02:07.919
and small amounts of iron and aluminum raw materials to about 1,450

35
00:02:07.919 --> 00:02:10.895
degrees Celsius in a rotary kiln.

36
00:02:10.895 --> 00:02:13.148
The product, called clinker,

37
00:02:13.148 --> 00:02:18.217
is ground with gypsum and often with supplementary cementitious

38
00:02:18.217 --> 00:02:22.079
materials such as fly ash or blast-furnace slag.

39
00:02:22.079 --> 00:02:25.952
The resulting powder hydrates when mixed with water,

40
00:02:25.952 --> 00:02:28.782
forming calcium-silicate-hydrate gel —

41
00:02:28.782 --> 00:02:33.250
the binding phase that gives hardened concrete its strength.

42
00:02:33.250 --> 00:02:36.737
The emissions come from two sources.

43
00:02:36.737 --> 00:02:41.368
The first is fuel combustion to reach kiln temperature.

44
00:02:41.368 --> 00:02:46.931
This roughly 40 percent share can be reduced with electrification,

45
00:02:46.931 --> 00:02:49.797
biomass, hydrogen, or waste heat —

46
00:02:49.797 --> 00:02:53.000
though each option has scaling limits.

47
00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:53.962
The second,

48
00:02:53.962 --> 00:02:59.474
larger source is the decomposition of calcium carbonate itself.

49
00:02:59.474 --> 00:03:04.182
As long as limestone is the primary calcium feedstock,

50
00:03:04.182 --> 00:03:08.105
CO2 is an intrinsic product of the chemistry.

51
00:03:08.105 --> 00:03:13.481
Alternative binders and clinkers aim to replace or reduce the lime

52
00:03:13.481 --> 00:03:16.658
content derived from calcium carbonate.

53
00:03:16.658 --> 00:03:22.392
Calcined clay combined with limestone can cut clinker factors by 30 to

54
00:03:22.392 --> 00:03:25.750
50 percent while maintaining performance.

55
00:03:25.750 --> 00:03:26.840
Geopolymers,

56
00:03:26.840 --> 00:03:33.017
made from alkali-activated aluminosilicates such as fly ash or slag,

57
00:03:33.017 --> 00:03:36.105
avoid Portland chemistry entirely.

58
00:03:36.105 --> 00:03:41.895
Belite-rich or calcium-sulfoaluminate clinkers can be fired at lower

59
00:03:41.895 --> 00:03:46.237
temperatures and absorb less limestone-derived CO2.

60
00:03:46.237 --> 00:03:51.670
And CO2-cured concrete keeps Portland cement chemistry but replaces

61
00:03:51.670 --> 00:03:55.887
part of the hydration pathway with rapid carbonation

62
00:03:55.887 --> 00:03:55.968
,

63
00:03:55.968 --> 00:04:00.915
turning CO2 into stable calcium carbonate while gaining early

64
00:04:00.915 --> 00:04:01.645
strength.

65
00:04:01.645 --> 00:04:06.749
None of these routes is yet deployable at the scale of ordinary

66
00:04:06.749 --> 00:04:07.316
cement.

67
00:04:07.316 --> 00:04:12.451
And all of them face materials-science bottlenecks that computation

68
00:04:12.451 --> 00:04:13.294
can address

69
00:04:13.294 --> 00:04:16.513
— provided the computation is trustworthy.

70
00:04:16.513 --> 00:04:20.039
Let's look at three discovery fronts.

71
00:04:20.039 --> 00:04:20.585
First,

72
00:04:20.585 --> 00:04:26.408
alternative binders: amorphous networks as the functional phase.

73
00:04:26.408 --> 00:04:32.002
The most promising alternative binders — slag, fly ash, calcined clay

74
00:04:32.002 --> 00:04:33.542
, and geopolymers —

75
00:04:33.542 --> 00:04:39.055
are not crystalline minerals that can be solved by X-ray diffraction

76
00:04:39.055 --> 00:04:41.974
and modeled with a single unit cell.

77
00:04:41.974 --> 00:04:43.822
They are glasses, gels,

78
00:04:43.822 --> 00:04:49.367
or nanocrystalline assemblages in which reactivity and durability are

79
00:04:49.367 --> 00:04:53.224
controlled by the distribution of silicon-oxygen

80
00:04:53.224 --> 00:04:57.724
, aluminum-oxygen, and calcium-oxygen bond environments.

81
00:04:57.916 --> 00:05:03.246
These materials are difficult to model with density functional theory

82
00:05:03.246 --> 00:05:08.527
because DFT is most reliable for well-defined crystalline unit cells.

83
00:05:08.527 --> 00:05:13.779
Amorphous or nanocrystalline models require large supercells and

84
00:05:13.779 --> 00:05:15.420
statistical sampling

85
00:05:15.420 --> 00:05:19.605
, making DFT prohibitively expensive for screening.

86
00:05:19.605 --> 00:05:22.322
Universal potentials are fast enough,

87
00:05:22.322 --> 00:05:27.314
but they are trained on bulk equilibrium structures and misrepresent

88
00:05:27.314 --> 00:05:31.206
the under-coordinated bonds that dominate dissolution

89
00:05:31.206 --> 00:05:33.408
, gelation, and precipitation.

90
00:05:33.408 --> 00:05:38.573
A predicted dissolution rate that is off by a factor of two or three

91
00:05:38.573 --> 00:05:41.763
is enough to misrank a binder formulation.

92
00:05:41.763 --> 00:05:45.263
The coordination problem is structural.

93
00:05:45.263 --> 00:05:47.808
In a crystalline quartz framework,

94
00:05:47.808 --> 00:05:52.373
silicon is tetrahedrally coordinated and oxygen is bridging —

95
00:05:52.373 --> 00:05:57.237
the local environment is close to the bulk training distribution.

96
00:05:57.237 --> 00:06:03.342
But in a partially dissolved slag grain or a nascent geopolymer gel,

97
00:06:03.342 --> 00:06:08.907
silicon may be present as Q1, Q2, or Q3 species with one, two,

98
00:06:08.907 --> 00:06:14.563
or three bridging oxygens, and aluminum may occupy tetrahedral,

99
00:06:14.563 --> 00:06:15.640
pentahedral,

100
00:06:15.640 --> 00:06:21.027
or octahedral sites depending on pH and charge compensation.

101
00:06:21.027 --> 00:06:25.186
These environments fall outside the bulk distribution,

102
00:06:25.186 --> 00:06:29.961
and universal potentials systematically soften their energies.

103
00:06:29.961 --> 00:06:35.152
Lupine's environment error field treats this as a measurable departure

104
00:06:35.152 --> 00:06:38.119
rather than an unknowable model failure.

105
00:06:38.119 --> 00:06:42.584
The field is anchored to observable reference environments and

106
00:06:42.584 --> 00:06:47.049
extrapolates to under-coordinated configurations with a smooth

107
00:06:47.049 --> 00:06:48.921
, bulk-constrained spline.

108
00:06:48.921 --> 00:06:51.314
For amorphous binder networks,

109
00:06:51.314 --> 00:06:56.498
corrected bond energies recover accurate dissolution and gelation

110
00:06:56.498 --> 00:06:57.295
energetics

111
00:06:57.295 --> 00:06:57.375
,

112
00:06:57.375 --> 00:07:02.878
so screens rank formulations by reactivity and durability rather than

113
00:07:02.878 --> 00:07:04.553
by training-set bias.

114
00:07:04.553 --> 00:07:10.632
Second, alternative clinkers: multi-component oxide spaces.

115
00:07:10.632 --> 00:07:16.088
These replace the dominant and most carbon-intensive phase in Portland

116
00:07:16.088 --> 00:07:18.660
cement with phases such as belite

117
00:07:18.660 --> 00:07:21.855
, ye'elimite, or ferrite solid solutions.

118
00:07:21.855 --> 00:07:26.572
Calcium-sulfoaluminate clinkers, for example,

119
00:07:26.572 --> 00:07:32.862
can be produced at 1,200 to 1,300 degrees rather than 1,450,

120
00:07:32.862 --> 00:07:35.692
and require less limestone,

121
00:07:35.692 --> 00:07:40.513
cutting process emissions by 20 to 35 percent.

122
00:07:40.513 --> 00:07:45.281
Belite-rich cements lower the lime saturation factor and can

123
00:07:45.281 --> 00:07:48.540
incorporate more supplementary materials.

124
00:07:48.540 --> 00:07:53.620
The challenge is that these clinkers involve multi-component oxide

125
00:07:53.620 --> 00:07:55.852
spaces whose phase equilibria

126
00:07:55.852 --> 00:07:57.468
, hydration pathways,

127
00:07:57.468 --> 00:08:02.856
and impurity sensitivities are far more complex than ordinary Portland

128
00:08:02.856 --> 00:08:03.395
cement.

129
00:08:03.395 --> 00:08:09.087
The number of candidate compositions exceeds 100,000 when dopants,

130
00:08:09.087 --> 00:08:13.658
substituents, and processing conditions are included.

131
00:08:13.658 --> 00:08:19.319
Universal potentials can screen this space at roughly 100,000 times

132
00:08:19.319 --> 00:08:20.671
the speed of DFT

133
00:08:20.671 --> 00:08:24.474
— but only if their rankings are trustworthy.

134
00:08:24.474 --> 00:08:29.000
And the ranking problem is aggravated by metastability.

135
00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:34.313
The best-performing clinker and hydrate combinations are often not the

136
00:08:34.313 --> 00:08:39.171
equilibrium assemblages predicted by convex-hull thermodynamics.

137
00:08:39.171 --> 00:08:41.315
Ettringite, AFm phases,

138
00:08:41.315 --> 00:08:47.094
and certain C-S-H compositions are metastable yet functionally

139
00:08:47.094 --> 00:08:48.027
essential.

140
00:08:48.027 --> 00:08:53.419
Standard computational screens that discard anything above the convex

141
00:08:53.419 --> 00:08:57.013
hull therefore discard the most useful phases.

142
00:08:57.013 --> 00:09:02.421
Lupine's verification layer addresses this by proving boundaries.

143
00:09:02.421 --> 00:09:06.888
It separates predictions that are supported by the measured error

144
00:09:06.888 --> 00:09:11.698
field from predictions that depend on synthesis conditions outside the

145
00:09:11.698 --> 00:09:12.934
correction domain.

146
00:09:12.934 --> 00:09:18.241
A belite-rich clinker whose hydrate assemblage is robustly ranked can

147
00:09:18.241 --> 00:09:20.395
be advanced with confidence.

148
00:09:20.395 --> 00:09:25.478
One whose ranking flips under plausible curing variations is flagged

149
00:09:25.478 --> 00:09:30.187
as unsupported rather than hidden behind an arbitrary stability

150
00:09:30.187 --> 00:09:30.711
cutoff.

151
00:09:30.711 --> 00:09:36.829
Third, CO2-cured concrete: barrier-controlled carbonation.

152
00:09:36.829 --> 00:09:42.230
Instead of emitting CO2 during calcination and later capturing it,

153
00:09:42.230 --> 00:09:47.630
CO2-cured concrete uses calcium-rich silicates that react directly

154
00:09:47.630 --> 00:09:51.639
with CO2 to form calcium carbonate and silica gel

155
00:09:51.639 --> 00:09:57.040
, producing early strength and sequestering carbon in the product.

156
00:09:57.040 --> 00:10:02.013
Some formulations gain compressive strength within hours.

157
00:10:02.188 --> 00:10:05.496
The materials challenge is kinetic.

158
00:10:05.496 --> 00:10:09.136
Carbonation proceeds through CO2 dissolution,

159
00:10:09.136 --> 00:10:14.152
diffusion through pores and increasingly dense product layers,

160
00:10:14.152 --> 00:10:18.035
and reaction at under-coordinated surface sites.

161
00:10:18.035 --> 00:10:24.233
As the carbonate layer thickens, CO2 diffusion becomes rate-limiting.

162
00:10:24.233 --> 00:10:29.370
Universal potentials underestimate the barriers for CO2 insertion and

163
00:10:29.370 --> 00:10:34.434
carbonate diffusion at under-coordinated surface sites because those

164
00:10:34.434 --> 00:10:39.125
transition states involve reduced coordination relative to bulk

165
00:10:39.125 --> 00:10:40.167
training data.

166
00:10:40.167 --> 00:10:44.893
Corrected carbonate formation and diffusion barriers change the

167
00:10:44.893 --> 00:10:48.720
ranking of candidate calcium-silicate compositions.

168
00:10:48.720 --> 00:10:54.225
A composition that appears to carbonate rapidly in a raw screen may be

169
00:10:54.225 --> 00:10:55.562
a false positive.

170
00:10:55.562 --> 00:11:00.711
A composition that looks sluggish may simply have been penalized by

171
00:11:00.711 --> 00:11:02.325
systematic softening.

172
00:11:02.325 --> 00:11:06.935
The correction recovers the true activation energies,

173
00:11:06.935 --> 00:11:11.720
enabling a materials-first design of CO2-cured binders.

174
00:11:11.720 --> 00:11:16.170
So why does computation fail across all three fronts,

175
00:11:16.170 --> 00:11:18.101
and how can it succeed?

176
00:11:18.101 --> 00:11:23.214
The common failure is the same defect-bulk asymmetry that corrupts

177
00:11:23.214 --> 00:11:25.693
predictions for battery cathodes

178
00:11:25.693 --> 00:11:29.799
, direct-air-capture sorbents, and methane catalysts.

179
00:11:29.799 --> 00:11:35.125
Universal potentials are trained on equilibrium bulk configurations

180
00:11:35.125 --> 00:11:36.795
where atoms have high

181
00:11:36.795 --> 00:11:39.259
, regular coordination numbers.

182
00:11:39.259 --> 00:11:44.421
The functional environments in cement — dissolved silicate species,

183
00:11:44.421 --> 00:11:48.659
gel pores, hydrate interfaces, and carbonation fronts —

184
00:11:48.659 --> 00:11:53.590
have coordination numbers and chemistries that fall outside this

185
00:11:53.590 --> 00:11:55.285
training distribution.

186
00:11:55.285 --> 00:12:00.957
A recent systematic survey found that they soften the potential energy

187
00:12:00.957 --> 00:12:05.575
surface by 15 to 60 percent in under-coordinated regions.

188
00:12:05.575 --> 00:12:09.062
This softening is not random noise.

189
00:12:09.062 --> 00:12:13.913
It has a smooth geometric dependence on local coordination and

190
00:12:13.913 --> 00:12:16.496
chemical deviation from the bulk.

191
00:12:16.496 --> 00:12:21.456
Lupine's environment error field exploits that regularity.

192
00:12:21.456 --> 00:12:23.635
The correction is analytic,

193
00:12:23.635 --> 00:12:29.201
so molecular dynamics and structural relaxations follow the corrected

194
00:12:29.201 --> 00:12:33.477
surface at nearly the same speed as the raw potential

195
00:12:33.477 --> 00:12:36.220
— with only 15.6 percent overhead.

196
00:12:36.220 --> 00:12:42.819
Blind prediction across 36 model and material combinations achieves a

197
00:12:42.819 --> 00:12:48.654
Pearson correlation of 0.906 with zero adjustable parameters.

198
00:12:48.654 --> 00:12:52.781
For cement, that rank-order preservation is critical —

199
00:12:52.781 --> 00:12:58.131
a 15 percent error in dissolution energy can invert the ranking of two

200
00:12:58.131 --> 00:12:59.583
binder formulations

201
00:12:59.583 --> 00:13:03.022
, sending experiments to the wrong candidate.

202
00:13:03.022 --> 00:13:08.904
Now, computational materials discovery has a credibility problem.

203
00:13:08.904 --> 00:13:13.933
Large-scale crystal-structure predictions have produced millions of

204
00:13:13.933 --> 00:13:15.359
candidate materials

205
00:13:15.359 --> 00:13:20.088
, but independent synthesis has validated only a tiny fraction.

206
00:13:20.088 --> 00:13:25.686
The so-called 0.2 percent synthesis problem reflects the gap between

207
00:13:25.686 --> 00:13:29.062
computable stability and makeable matter.

208
00:13:29.062 --> 00:13:29.914
For cement,

209
00:13:29.914 --> 00:13:35.261
the problem is worse because the most interesting phases are not even

210
00:13:35.261 --> 00:13:36.733
on the convex hull.

211
00:13:36.733 --> 00:13:42.232
Lupine's verification layer uses build-locked Lean 4 theorems to state

212
00:13:42.232 --> 00:13:44.667
what is proven and what is not.

213
00:13:44.667 --> 00:13:51.009
The current library contains 77 theorems with zero sorry proofs.

214
00:13:51.009 --> 00:13:55.440
The system can distinguish three classes of claim: predictions

215
00:13:55.440 --> 00:13:58.084
supported by the measured error field

216
00:13:58.084 --> 00:14:01.371
; predictions bounded by explicit uncertainty;

217
00:14:01.371 --> 00:14:05.873
and claims that are genuinely synthesis-dependent and cannot be

218
00:14:05.873 --> 00:14:08.088
supported by the current model.

219
00:14:08.088 --> 00:14:11.443
That third class is not a failure.

220
00:14:11.443 --> 00:14:13.601
It is a guardrail.

221
00:14:13.601 --> 00:14:18.380
It prevents a team from promising a phase whose stability cannot be

222
00:14:18.380 --> 00:14:21.733
separated from the curing path used to make it.

223
00:14:21.733 --> 00:14:24.956
This discipline matters commercially.

224
00:14:24.956 --> 00:14:30.091
Investors and offtake partners routinely ask whether a predicted

225
00:14:30.091 --> 00:14:31.535
binder will scale.

226
00:14:31.535 --> 00:14:38.088
A probability value or a DFT energy alone cannot answer that question.

227
00:14:38.088 --> 00:14:43.489
A machine-checked boundary between supported and unsupported claims

228
00:14:43.489 --> 00:14:43.812
can.

229
00:14:43.812 --> 00:14:49.100
Cement is often treated as a special case — a commodity so cheap,

230
00:14:49.100 --> 00:14:50.320
so established,

231
00:14:50.320 --> 00:14:55.364
and so geographically fragmented that innovation moves slowly.

232
00:14:55.364 --> 00:15:00.049
That view misses the underlying computational structure.

233
00:15:00.049 --> 00:15:05.062
The materials that could decarbonize cement are not exotic.

234
00:15:05.062 --> 00:15:10.864
They are amorphous oxides, metastable hydrates, carbonated silicates,

235
00:15:10.864 --> 00:15:13.386
and multi-component clinkers —

236
00:15:13.386 --> 00:15:18.936
the same classes of materials that appear in batteries, catalysts,

237
00:15:18.936 --> 00:15:21.206
sorbents, and refrigerants.

238
00:15:21.206 --> 00:15:24.351
The failure modes are identical.

239
00:15:24.556 --> 00:15:30.197
The seven target areas in this series — water, air, methane,

240
00:15:30.197 --> 00:15:34.992
refrigerants, critical minerals, PFAS, and cement —

241
00:15:34.992 --> 00:15:36.917
share one conclusion.

242
00:15:36.917 --> 00:15:41.456
The bottleneck is not a shortage of candidate materials.

243
00:15:41.456 --> 00:15:45.206
It is a shortage of trustworthy predictions.

244
00:15:45.206 --> 00:15:48.862
Trust comes from measuring the shape of the error,

245
00:15:48.862 --> 00:15:51.421
correcting it with analytic forces,

246
00:15:51.421 --> 00:15:54.785
and proving which predictions can be believed.

247
00:15:54.785 --> 00:16:00.395
Cement, with its 2.8 gigatons of CO2 per year and its amorphous,

248
00:16:00.395 --> 00:16:02.236
metastable chemistry,

249
00:16:02.236 --> 00:16:08.022
is one of the hardest and largest places to apply that discipline.

250
00:16:08.022 --> 00:16:11.667
It is also one of the most consequential.
